'''Micky van de Ven''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈmɪki vɑn də ˈvɛn|lang}}; born 19 April 2001) is a Dutch professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays either as a [[centre-back]] or [[left-back]] for {{English football updater|TottenhH}} club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]]. Known for his ball-playing abilities and physicality, he is also one of the fastest players in the world.<ref>{{cite web |last=Churchill |first=Max |last2=Jeevathayalan |first2=Vijievan |date=7 January 2025 |title=The 20 fastest players in football history have been ranked - Thierry Henry 7th |url=https://www.givemesport.com/fastest-players-in-football-history-ranked/ |access-date=9 January 2026 |website=GiveMeSport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=6 February 2024 |title=Van de Ven becomes fastest Premier League player |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/3884168 |access-date=9 January 2026 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Top 10 Fastest Football Players in History |url=https://vocal.media/art/top-10-fastest-football-players-in-history |access-date=9 January 2026 |website=Art}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=1 March 2025 |title=13 Fastest Footballers in the World 2025 |url=https://thepfsa.co.uk/fastest-footballers/ |access-date=9 January 2026 |website=The PFSA}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Van de Ven began his career with [[FC Volendam|Volendam]], and made his first team debut against [[Jong PSV]] in the [[Eerste Divisie]], going on to make 19 appearances during the [[2019–20 Eerste Divisie|2019–20 season]].<ref name="lightning">{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/micky-van-de-ven-who-is-wolfsburg-s-lightning-fast-dutch-defender-23943|title=Micky van de Ven: who is Wolfsburg's lightning-fast Dutch defender?|website=[[Bundesliga]]|access-date=7 October 2023}}</ref> He assumed the captaincy during his [[2020–21 Eerste Divisie|first full season]] and scored twice in 26 appearances as Volendam reached the promotion play-offs.<ref name="lightning" />

Van de Ven transferred to German club [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in 2021 for a fee of £3.15&nbsp;million<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66097738|title=A 'Cruyffian' talent set for Premier League move?|work=BBC Sport |date=7 July 2023 }}</ref> and played all but one of the team's [[Bundesliga]] matches during the [[2022–23 Bundesliga|2022–23 season]], scoring his only goal in a 2–0 win against [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref name="lightning" /> Van de Ven recorded the highest top speed of any defender in the Bundesliga that season, at {{Convert|22.3|mph|km/h}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Micky van de Ven: who is Wolfsburg's lightning-fast Dutch defender? |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/micky-van-de-ven-who-is-wolfsburg-s-lightning-fast-dutch-defender-23943|website=[[Bundesliga]]|access-date=10 November 2023}}</ref>

=== Tottenham Hotspur ===

==== 2023–24 ====
On 8 August 2023, it was announced that van de Ven had signed a six-year deal with [[Premier League]] club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 August 2023 |title=Van de Ven arrives from VfL Wolfsburg |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/august/van-de-ven-arrives-from-vfl-wolfsburg/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231208115821/https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/august/van-de-ven-arrives-from-vfl-wolfsburg/ |archive-date=8 December 2023 |access-date=8 August 2023 |publisher=[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> The transfer cost an initial fee of £34.5 million and a potential total fee of £43 million, equalling the club's record fee for a centre-back in [[Cristian Romero (footballer, born 1998)|Cristian Romero]] the year before.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spurs complete Van de Ven signing |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4757896/2023/08/08/van-de-ven-spurs-transfer-complete/|website=[[The Athletic]]|access-date=8 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12914269/micky-van-de-ven-tottenham-complete-lb43m-deal-to-sign-wolfsburg-defender|title=Micky van de Ven: Tottenham complete £43m deal to sign Wolfsburg defender|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

Van de Ven debuted on 13 August during the first matchday of the [[2023–24 Premier League]] season, starting in an away match against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/football/2023/08/13/spurs-kick-off-post-harry-kane-era-with-2-2-draw-at-brentford/| title=Spurs kick off post-Harry Kane era with 2–2 draw at Brentford| work=The National| date=13 August 2023| access-date=19 August 2023}}</ref> On 7 October 2023, he scored his first goal in English football in Tottenham's 1–0 win at Kenilworth Road against [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jess|last=Anderson|title=Luton Town 0–1 Tottenham Hotspur |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66969158 |work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=7 October 2023}}</ref>

On 6 November 2023, van de Ven was substituted with a hamstring injury during a game against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Team news {{!}} Van de Ven, Maddison, Richarlison & Davies updates {{!}} Wolves vs Spurs |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/november/team-news-van-de-ven-maddison-richarlison-davies-updates-wolves-vs-spurs/|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|access-date=10 August 2023}}</ref> He returned from injury in a 2–2 draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 14 January 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5203409/2024/01/16/van-de-ven-comeback-boost/|title="Ridiculous" Micky van de Ven's recovery from injury should be transformative for Tottenham|date=16 January 2024|website=The Athletic|access-date=17 January 2024}}</ref> Later that month, during a match against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on 31 January, he was recorded as the Premier League's fastest ever player at {{convert|37.38|km/h}} since data collection began in 2020–21.<ref>{{cite web |date=6 February 2024 |title=Van de Ven becomes fastest Premier League player |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3884168 |access-date=6 February 2024 |publisher=[[Premier League]]}}</ref>

On 10 May 2024, van de Ven was awarded Tottenham's Player of the Season award at the Official Supporters' Clubs award night ceremony, having started 28 of the club's 38 games up until that point.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Micky completes clean sweep of Player of the Season awards |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2024/may/micky-van-de-ven-completes-clean-sweep-of-player-of-the-season-awards/ |access-date=2024-05-18 |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2024–25 ====
Van de Ven suffered several injuries during the [[2024–25 Premier League]] season. On 30 October 2024, during a [[EFL Cup]] match against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], he was injured and would not return until 8 December in a match against Chelsea, playing 79 minutes before being substituted. His next appearance for the club would not come until 30 January 2025, with a 45-minute appearance in the [[UEFA Europa League]] against [[IF Elfsborg]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=30 October 2024 |title=Timo Werner sparks Tottenham's Carabao Cup win over Manchester City |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/oct/30/tottenham-manchester-city-carabao-cup-match-report |access-date=2025-02-18 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Team news {{!}} Ange's update on Micky van de Ven |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2025/february/team-news-anges-update-on-micky-van-de-ven/ |access-date=2025-02-18 |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |language=en}}</ref> Despite his injury-hampered season, van de Ven was again recorded as the Premier League's fastest player, with a top speed of {{convert|37.1|km/h}}.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4272290| title=PL fastes players 24/25| work=Premier League| first=Ali| last=Tweedale| date=25 March 2025| access-date=25 June 2025}}</ref>

Van de Ven started the [[2025 UEFA Europa League final]] and delivered a crucial goal line clearance to help secure a 1–0 victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], securing his first major career honour and Tottenham Hotspur's first trophy in 17 years.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Burt|first=Jason |date=21 May 2025 |title=Ange Postecoglou keeps promise and ends Spurs' 17-year trophy drought |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2025/05/21/europa-league-final-live-score-tottenham-man-utd-watch/ |access-date=2025-05-21 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== 2025–26 ====
Van de Ven captained Spurs for the first time on 30 September 2025, in a 2–2 draw away against [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]]; he scored Tottenham's first goal of the night.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-10-01 |title=Micky van de Ven hoped for a better Tottenham performance on his special night |url=https://www.wiltsglosstandard.co.uk/sport/national/25507797.micky-van-de-ven-hoped-better-tottenham-performance-special-night/ |access-date=2025-10-02 |website=Wilts and Gloucestershire Standard |language=en}}</ref>

On 4 November, Van de Ven made a box-to-box solo run to score the third goal in a 4–0 win over [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] in the Champions League.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-04 |title=Tottenham player ratings vs Copenhagen: Give Micky van de Ven the Puskas Award! Defender's stunning solo goal caps crushing Champions League win for 10-man Spurs
 |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/tottenham-player-ratings-vs-copenhagen-micky-van-de-ven-champions-league/blt0bdb77913419911e |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=Goal.com |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
In October 2022, Van de Ven was included in the preliminary [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/nieuws/nederlands-elftal/80493/van-gaal-neemt-39-spelers-op-voorlopige-selectie-voor-wk |title=Van Gaal neemt 39 spelers op in voorlopige selectie voor WK |trans-title=Van Gaal includes 39 players in provisional squad for World Cup |publisher=[[Royal Dutch Football Association]] |date=21 October 2022 |access-date=12 November 2022 |language=nl}}</ref> He captained the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] at the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|Under-21 Euro 2023]].<ref name="auto"/>

In August 2023, he received his first official call-up to the Netherlands senior national team by head coach [[Ronald Koeman]], for two [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] matches against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Drie debutanten in definitieve selectie Oranje |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/nieuws/nederlands-elftal-mannen/80965/drie-debutanten-definitieve-selectie-oranje |access-date=1 September 2023 |publisher=[[KNVB]]|date=1 September 2023|language=nl}}</ref>

On 13 October 2023, Van de Ven debuted for the Dutch senior squad in a UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying match against [[France national football team|France]], replacing [[Nathan Aké]] in the 80th minute.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Debutanten Van de Ven en Maatsen tegen Griekenland op tribune|trans-title=Debutants Van de Ven and Maatsen in the stands against Greece|url=https://www.rtl.nl/sport/voetbal/artikel/5406319/debutanten-van-de-ven-en-maatsen-tegen-griekenland-op-tribune|website=[[RTL Nederland]]|date=13 October 2023|language=nl}}</ref>

On 29 May 2024, Van de Ven was named in the Netherlands' squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5526712/2024/05/29/netherlands-euro-2024-squad-confirmed/|title= Netherlands Euro 2024 squad: Ian Maatsen dropped, Georginio Wijnaldum and Daley Blind retained |date=29 May 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|website=The New York Times}}</ref>

He scored his first goal for the Netherlands on 10 June 2025 during an 8–0 win against [[Malta national football team|Malta]] in [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group G|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref name=Malta />

On 27 May 2026, he was named in the Netherlands squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

